fix(server): block path-traversal in sim.save_replay / sim.load_replay

The `sim.save_replay` and `sim.load_replay` JSON-RPC handlers previously
forwarded the wire `path` straight to `Simulation::save_replay` /
`Simulation::load_replay_from_file`, both of which resolve any path the
caller provides. An authenticated JSON-RPC client could therefore read
or overwrite arbitrary files outside the bridge `saves/` directory (e.g.
`../../etc/passwd`), and `sim.load_replay` additionally replaced the live
simulation state.

Two layers of defense:

1. `parse_replay_path` in `jsonrpc.rs` now rejects every traversal
   primitive we can detect from the string alone: empty, length > 255,
   `/`, `\`, `..`, NUL / LF / CR, and any extension other than
   `.civreplay`. All rejections surface as JSON-RPC `-32602 INVALID_PARAMS`
   so legitimate clients see a clear contract violation rather than an
   opaque I/O error.

2. `replay_path_under` in `ws_bridge.rs` is the defense-in-depth: it
   canonicalizes the candidate path against a fixed `saves/` root and
   rejects anything that escapes (including symlinks) before the engine
   touches the filesystem. Both `SaveReplay` and `LoadReplay` dispatch
   arms now route through it; if a future refactor loosens the parser,
   the containment check still holds.

Regression tests cover both layers: traversal patterns, NUL smuggling,
wrong extensions, pathological length, symlink escape (Unix), and the
happy path. The previous `parse_replay_path` test fixture
`saves/x.civreplay` is replaced with `replay-20260623.civreplay` since
subdirectory paths are no longer accepted.
